  display: "December 10, 1987 (Los Angeles, California, USA)"
bio:
  short: "Russian-American violinist, widely regarded as one of the greatest violinists of all time"
  full: |
    Jascha Heifetz was born on February 2, 1901 in Vilnius, Lithuania (then part of the Russian Empire) to Leopold Heifetz, a violinist and teacher. He showed extraordinary musical talent from an early age, beginning violin lessons at age 3 and performing publicly by age 5.

    In 1906, he entered the Vilnius Music School under Ilya Malats, and in 1907 his family moved to Saint Petersburg where he studied under Leopold Auer at the Saint Petersburg Conservatory. By age 11, he was performing full violin concertos.

    1917 was a pivotal year - after the October Revolution, Heifetz and his family emigrated to the United States. On November 27, 1917, he made his legendary debut at Carnegie Hall in New York under conductor Walter Damrosch. The concert caused a sensation, with critics calling him "the greatest violinist in the world."

    Heifetz became an American citizen in 1925. Known for his impeccable technique, pure tone, and unique interpretations, he owned several famous instruments including the "Dolphin" Stradivarius (1714), which he acquired in 1951.

    From 1962 to 1972, Heifetz taught at the University of California, Los Angeles. Among his students were many renowned violinists. In his later years, he focused primarily on teaching and recording.

    Jascha Heifetz died on December 10, 1987 in Los Angeles from kidney failure. He is buried at Mount Sinai Memorial Park in Los Angeles.
